Cell["\<\
Pie charts are inherently harder to read than the stacked bar chart that does \
the same job: the proportions of the different quantities in a pie chart are \
proportional to the perimeter of an arc of a circle, compared to the length \
of a straight line in the case of the stacked bar chart.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.787580672304227*^9, 3.7875807590569572`*^9}, 
   3.787580796457796*^9, {3.787580867319409*^9, 3.787580875546632*^9}, {
   3.787580997007011*^9, 
   3.7875810297905903`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"f75ede72-5e25-4d5a-8300-\
d066e32e2652"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["The scatter plot", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.78759136054237*^9, 
  3.787591366238138*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"9b4c2101-53d9-4714-99b3-\
12e57e68dfe1"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Scatter plots are a good way to visualise how two numerical quantities are \
related to each other. In contrast to bar charts, scatter plots are used for \
purely ",
 StyleBox["numerical ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "quantities, not categorical data. For example, temperature and pressure at \
a given location; or inflation and average income of some country. Scatter \
plots are especially useful for finding correlations between quantities.\n\n\
In their simplest form, a scatter plot is defined for two numerical \
quantities. To exemplify, let us use the wealth, as measured by the GDP per \
capita, and the literacy rate, of the set of all countries for which these \
quantities are recorded in Mathematica\[CloseCurlyQuote]s database:"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7875914325498247`*^9, 3.787591696614215*^9}, {
   3.7875917318456917`*^9, 3.7875918164620557`*^9}, {3.7875944527683115`*^9, 
   3.7875944740448895`*^9}, 
   3.787663819913216*^9},ExpressionUUID->"84a2c229-25b0-45d5-897a-\
8744f52304c4"],

