Cell["\<\
With the logarithmic scale, we see that in fact the India\[CloseCurlyQuote]s \
and China\[CloseCurlyQuote]s wealth has in fact increased since the 1960\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]s, but this increase was hidden by the scale of the \
previous plot. This is an important lesson: changes in quantities may not be \
visible in a plot if the scales are not chosen properly.

Notice, on the other hand, that the decrease in the US\[CloseCurlyQuote]s \
wealth is barely visible in the logarithmic plot!

Another way you could have visualised the changes in wealth for India and \
China is by not plotting the US\[CloseCurlyQuote]s data on the same graph:  \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7878404151461706`*^9, 3.7878406817661*^9}, {
  3.787840725951682*^9, 3.787840729124484*^9}, {3.787840853767301*^9, 
  3.787840913701765*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"f1fbad11-ff49-4c33-95f1-\
e3a5e13dec2e"],

